{"contentApi":{"id":"world/2012/dec/20/newtown-shooting-victims-profiles","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webPublicationDate":1356035640000,"webTitle":"Newtown school shootings: the 27 victims","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/dec/20/newtown-shooting-victims-profiles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/2012/dec/20/newtown-shooting-victims-profiles","fields":{"trailText":"<p>Families and friends of the victims have spoken publicly about their loved ones in the week since the Sandy Hook shootings</p>","headline":"Newtown school shootings: the 27 victims","body":"<p><a name=\"Charlotte\"> </a></p><h2><a name=\"Charlotte\">Charlotte Bacon, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Charlotte, who would have turned seven in February, had curly, dark red hair and a &quot;big personality&quot; her uncle John Hagen, <a href=\"http://www.newsday.com/news/nation/sandy-hook-s-youngest-victims-remembered-as-innocent-children-1.4337532.\">told Newsday</a>. </p><p>She was smart, outgoing, precocious and persistent, he said.</p><p>&quot;She could carry on a conversation with any adult,&quot; said Hagen. &quot;She challenged my sister every day. She knew how to get what she wanted.&quot;</p><p>Charlotte's mother, Joann, bought her a pink dress, her favourite colour, and white boots for the holidays. Every day, the little girl would beg her to let her wear the outfit early. On Friday, the last day of her life, her mother finally relented.</p><p>&quot;This girl was definitely going places,&quot; her uncle said. Her nine-year-old brother, Guy, was also at Sandy Hook on Friday but wasn't harmed.</p><p>Charlotte also loved being a girl scout, and her mother was her troop leader.</p><p>&quot;There were 10 girls in the group,&quot; Hagen said. &quot;Only five are left.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Daniel\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Daniel\">Daniel Barden, 7</a></h2><p></p><p>The family of Daniel Barden, a budding athlete, member of the swim team and soccer player, said he was &quot;fearless in the pursuit of happiness in life&quot; and was a &quot;constant source of joy&quot; in theirs.</p><p>In a statement, Mark and Jackie Barden said their seven-year-old, who was the youngest of three, earned his missing two front teeth and ripped jeans.</p><p>&quot;Words really cannot express what a special boy Daniel was. Such a light. Always smiling, unfailingly polite, incredibly affectionate, fair and so thoughtful towards others, imaginative in play, both intelligent and articulate in conversation: in all, a constant source of laughter and joy,&quot; the family said, in a statement reported by <a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324481204578181244231543014.htm\">the Wall Street Journal</a>. </p><p>The Bardens said their son &quot;embodied everything that is wholesome and innocent in the world. Our hearts break over losing him and for the many other families suffering loss.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Olivia\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Olivia\">Olivia Engel, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>A photo of Olivia Rose Engel on the &quot;Friends of the Engel Family Fund&quot; Facebook page shows her sitting behind the steering wheel of a boat wearing oversized sunglasses, smiling. Another shows her wearing white wings, holding a golden star over her head. She was supposed to be the angel at the Christmas pageant in the St Rose of Lima Church on Saturday, her cousin, John Engel, acting as a spokesman for Olivia's parents, Brian and Shannon, said.</p><p>&quot;She was a beautiful outgoing child&quot; who took tennis, ballet and hip-hop dance lessons, Engel told television news stations. &quot;She was not a shy child. She would light up a room with her smile and her sense of humour.&quot;</p><p>He said Olivia was a &quot;great big sister for Brayden&quot;, her younger brother, who is three, and every night led grace at the family dinner table. Her favourite colours were pink and purple.</p><p>Engel said that Olivia's mother was a local teacher, in a family of three generations of teachers.</p><p><a name=\"Josephine\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Josephine\">Josephine Gay, 7</a></h2><p></p><p>Josephine Grace Gay liked to ride her bike in the street and set up lemonade stands in the summer, according to a neighbour quoted in the Wall Street Journal.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/newstimes/obituary.aspx?pid=161794164#fbLoggedOut\">Josephine's obituary </a>said many friends and family described her as a &quot;gift&quot;. It read: &quot;She lived seven years, inspiring friends and family with her beautiful smile, loving heart, and playful spirit.&quot;</p><p>In celebration of her joyful and giving spirit, a charitable fund is being set up in her honour.</p><h2>Dylan Hockley, 6</h2><p>Images of Dylan beam out from photos his mother, Nicole, has posted on her Twitter page. In one, he is &quot;Super Dylan&quot; dressed in a Superman outfit. In another, he poses with his brother Jake, eight. His family, who chose Newtown when they moved from the UK, for the community and the school, said they did not regret their choice. They said the family's happiness had been &quot;limitless&quot; in their new home.</p><p>He died in the arms of Anne Marie Murphy, an educator who was taking care of his special educational needs.</p><p>&quot;We take great comfort in knowing that Dylan was not alone when he died, but was wrapped in the arms of his amazing aide, Anne Marie Murphy,&quot; <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/dec/19/newtown-shooting-british-family-victim\">his parents said, in a statement</a>. &quot;Dylan loved Mrs Murphy so much and pointed at her picture on our refrigerator every day.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Madeleine\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Madeleine\">Madeleine Hsu, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Madeleine's outfits of sunny, floral dresses matched her personality.</p><p>&quot;She was a sweet, unique, bright, sparkling, determined little girl,&quot; her family said in a statement about her. &quot;She was an avid reader who loved running and dancing. She was a born leader.&quot;</p><p>Karen Dryer, a neighbour of the Hsu family, described the &quot;tiny&quot; little girl she knew as Maddie as a &quot;very upbeat and kind&quot; girl who loved bright, flowery dresses. Dryer <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-shooting-victims-20121217,0,2658399.story\">told the Los Angeles Times</a> that Madeleine and another little girl, Caroline Previdi, who was killed in the tragedy, would reassure her son, Logan, not to be scared when going to school.</p><p><a name=\"Catherine\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Catherine\">Catherine Hubbard, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Catherine Violet Hubbard will be &quot;remembered for her passion of animals and constant smile&quot;.</p><p>Her parents Jennifer and Matthew Hubbard and older brother, Frederick William, asked that all donations in memory of &quot;our beautiful daughter Catherine Violet&quot; go to the Newtown animal shelter.</p><p>&quot;Her family prays that she, all the students of Sandy Hook Elementary, and all those affected by this brutal event find peace in their hearts,&quot; <a href=\"http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/newstimes/obituary.aspx?n=catherine-hubbard&amp;pid=161771328&amp;fhid=11690#fbLoggedOut\">said an obituary</a> in Newstimes. </p><p><a name=\"Chase\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Chase\">Chase Kowalski, 7</a></h2><p></p><p>Chase Kowalski was a boy who was always outside, riding his bicycle or playing in the backyard. Last week, he visited his neighbour Kevin Grimes, and told him about completing and winning his first mini-triathlon.</p><p>&quot;You couldn't think of a better child,&quot; Grimes, a father of five children who all attended Sandy Hook, told the Associated Press. He spoke of Chase only in the present tense.</p><p>Another neighbour, Suzanne Baumann, told the Wall Street Journal that Chase was &quot;very receptive to people. He was a beautiful child, an amazing child&quot; and the &quot;apple of his parents' eye&quot;.</p><p><a name=\"Jesse\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Jesse\">Jesse Lewis, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Jesse Lewis's mother said her son lived life with &quot;vigour and passion&quot; and love and was &quot;wise and soulful beyond his years&quot;.</p><p>&quot;Jesse was such an incredible light,&quot; his mother, Scarlett Lewis, said in a email on Sunday to the Wall Street Journal. &quot;So bright and full of love. He lived life with vigour and passion … brave and true.&quot;</p><p>Raised in Sandy Hook with his brother, JT, and a home full of animals, including horses, dogs and a mini-donkey, Jesse was learning to ride horses, according to family friends.</p><p>His mother told the newspaper that she was told he had run into the hall to help. &quot;I can only hope this meant he had less fear and went quickly in his bravery. … It is unbelievable to us that Jesse is now in heaven with Jesus.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Ana\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Ana\">Ana Marquez-Greene, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Ana moved to Connecticut with her family just two months before she was killed. Ana's grandmother, Elba Marquez, said they moved from Canada and were drawn in part by the school's stellar reputation.</p><p>Marquez had just visited her granddaughter's new home over Thanksgiving. She told the AP: &quot;It was a beautiful place, just beautiful. What happened does not match up with the place where they live.&quot;</p><p>The grandmother's brother, Jorge Marquez, said the child's nine-year-old brother, Isaiah also was at the school but escaped safely. He confirmed that Ana's father is the Canadian jazz saxophonist, Jimmy Greene, who wrote on Facebook that he was trying to &quot;work through this nightmare&quot;.</p><p>&quot;As much as she's needed here and missed by her mother, brother and me, Ana beat us all to paradise,&quot; Greene wrote. &quot;I love you sweetie girl.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"James\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"James\">James Mattioli, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>James, or &quot;J&quot;, was a &quot;numbers guy&quot; who loved math. He would come up with insights beyond his years to explain the relationships between numbers or to work out ways of adding or subtracting them, his obituary said.</p><p>He loved the concept of googolplex, which a friend taught him. An energetic little boy, he was always out of bed first, loved being outdoors and swam &quot;like a fish&quot; in his grandparents' pool. <a href=\"http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ctpost/obituary.aspx?n=James-Mattioli&amp;pid=161773044#fbLoggedOut\">In an obituary</a> to &quot;Our Beloved Prince&quot; his parents, Mark and Cindy, said he loved to wear shorts and T-shirts in any weather. He would use gel to spike his hair, sing at the top of his lungs and ask: &quot;How old do I have to be to sing on a stage?&quot;. At school, he was &quot;working very hard to advance his reading at first grade&quot;.</p><p>He and his big sister, Anna, were the &quot;best of friends, going to school together, playing games together, and making endless drawings and crafts together&quot; his family said.</p><p>Thoughtful and considerate, he would always welcome guests at the backdoor with &quot;a hug and his contagious smile&quot;.</p><p><a name=\"Grace\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Grace\">Grace McDonnell, 7</a></h2><p></p><p>On the last day of her life, a smiling Grace Audrey McDonnell skipped to the school bus, waving and blowing her mother kisses goodbye. The little girl, who turned seven in November, loved art and her dream was to live on the beach and be a painter, her mother said.</p><p>&quot;Grace had such a great spirit. She was a kind and gentle soul,&quot; Lynn McDonnell said in an interview together with her husband, Chris. Speaking to Anderson Cooper on CNN, she said: &quot;I take comfort that she's with friends, and she's up there with her wonderful principal.&quot;</p><h2>Emilie Parker, 6</h2><p>Emilie was a bright, creative six-year-old who carried her pencils and markers around with her, never missing the chance to draw a picture or make a card. She was a mentor to her little sisters, aged three and four, and was teaching them to dance and read.</p><p>Her father, Robbie Parker, one of the first parents to talk publicly about his loss, described the beautiful, blond, always-smiling girl who loved to try new things, except foods.</p><p>&quot;I'm so blessed to be her dad,&quot; he said. The family have set up the Emilie Parker fund to help those affected by the shooting.</p><p><a name=\"Jack\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Jack\">Jack Pinto, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Jack Armistead Pinto was &quot;an incredibly loving and vivacious&quot; boy, with a &quot;lively and giving spirit and steely determination,&quot; according to <a href=\"http://newtownbee.com/Obituaries/2012/12-December/2012-12-16__12-37-27/Jack+Armistead+Pinto\">an obituary in the Newtown Bee</a>. Jack was an &quot;avid participant&quot; in a variety of sports, including flag football, basketball, wrestling, and snow-skiing and was a huge fan of the New York Giants.</p><p>Victor Cruz, the team's star wide receiver and Jack's idol, reached out to the Pinto family after learning that Jack was to be buried in the #80 Jersey he wore while watching his hero play.</p><p>&quot;In life and in death, Jack will forever be remembered for the immeasurable joy he brought to all who had the pleasure of knowing him, a joy whose wide reach belied his six short years,&quot; Jack's obituary said.</p><h2>Noah Pozner, 6</h2><p>Noah was &quot;smart as a whip&quot;, gentle but with a rambunctious streak, his uncle, Alexis Haller, said. Noah's twin sister and best friend, Arielle, was in a different classroom at the time of the shooting and survived. Together with their eight-year-old sister, Sophia, they were inseparable.</p><p>&quot;They were always playing together, they loved to do things together,&quot; Haller said.</p><p>Haller said his nephew loved to read and liked to figure out how things worked mechanically. For his birthday two weeks ago, he got a new Wii.</p><p>&quot;He was just a really lively, smart kid,&quot; Haller said. &quot;He would have become a great man, I think. He would have grown up to be a great dad.&quot;</p><h2>Caroline Previdi, 6</h2><p>Caroline Phoebe Previdi was a sweet child with an infectious smile who loved to draw and dance. Her mother, Sandy, speaking at her funeral at the St Rose of Lima Church in Newtown, described her daughter as her precious angel.</p><p>&quot;She was happy. She was innocent. She danced everywhere she went,&quot; Pam Fehrs, whose daughters went to jazz and ballet classes with Caroline, <a href=\"http://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Funeral-for-Caroline-Phoebe-Previdi-6-4133265.php#ixzz2Fbb54d8h\">told the Stamford Advocate</a>.</p><p><a href=\"http://newtownbee.com/Obituaries/2012/12-December/2012-12-18__11-09-30/Caroline+Phoebe+Previdi\">Caroline's obituary</a>, in the Newtown Bee, said: &quot;Her smile brought happiness to everyone she touched.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Jessica\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Jessica\">Jessica Rekos, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Jessica loved horses and would read about them, write about them, draw them and watch movies about them. When she turned 10, her parents, Rich and Krista Rekos promised her, she would have a horse of her own. In the meantime, they bought her new cowboy boots and a cowboy hat for Christmas.</p><p>In a statement, the Rekoses described their daughter as &quot;a creative, beautiful little girl who loved playing with her little brothers, Travis and Shane&quot;.</p><p>She was &quot;our rock&quot;, they said. &quot;She had an answer for everything, she didn't miss a trick, and she outsmarted us every time.&quot; A thoughtful planner, she was &quot;our little CEO&quot;.</p><p>&quot;We cannot imagine our life without her.&quot;</p><h2>Avielle Richman, 6</h2><p>Avielle Rose Richman, known as Avie, loved horses, Harry Potter, the colour red, and archery for a spell after watching the Disney movie Brave.</p><p>She moved from San Diego to Newtown two years ago with her parents, Jeremy Richman and Jennifer Hensel. Her new life on the east coast was chronicled in a blog called &quot;Avielle's Adventures&quot;. It is filled with the joys and milestones of her short life, birthday parties, riding stables and trips. One post, which has a picture of a smiling Avielle sitting on the window sill, reads: &quot;We can't believe it. Our little hummingbird is starting first grade tomorrow.&quot;</p><p>&quot;They still call Avielle their California girl,&quot; Melissa Stewart, a family friend,<a href=\"http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/dec/17/school-shooting-victim-loved-torrey-pines-beach/\"> told the San Diego Union-Tribune</a>. &quot;When they first moved here, it was hard to keep shoes on Avielle because she was so used to running barefoot on the beach in San Diego.&quot;</p><p><a name=\"Benjamin\"></a></p><h2><a name=\"Benjamin\">Benjamin Wheeler, 6</a></h2><p></p><p>Benjamin never walked when he could run, a boy with &quot;no dimmer switch&quot;, his grandfather said.</p><p>Carmen Lobis described him as a kid in overdrive, who was &quot;exceptional&quot; and could play the piano beautifully.</p><p>&quot;He always blew us kisses and he would say: 'Catch it and put it in your heart,'&quot; Lobis <a href=\"http://www.denverpost.com/ci_22215616/benjamin-wheeler-boy-boundless-energy\">told the Denver Post</a>. &quot;The last time I saw him was two weeks ago when I dropped him off at Sunday school.&quot;</p><p>Lobis said he told the boy's mother, Francine, a music educator, he was going to accomplish many things in his life. &quot;He was really going to do something special,&quot; he said.</p><h2>Allison Wyatt, 6</h2><p>Allison was a kind-hearted little girl, who loved drawing and would turn her house into an art studio with rows of pictures taped to the walls.</p><p>&quot;She was a sweet, creative, funny, intelligent little girl who had an amazing life ahead of her,&quot; said her parents, Cheyanne and Ben Wyatt, in her obituary. They said she would sometimes make them laugh so hard they cried. &quot;Our world is a lot darker now that she's gone. We love and miss her so much.&quot;</p><p><a href=\"http://newtownbee.com/Obituaries/2012/12-December/2012-12-18__17-15-10/Allison+Wyatt\">Allison's obituary</a> in the Newtown Bee, said she was: &quot;A kind-hearted little girl who had a lot of love to give, she formed special bonds with most people who spent any amount of time with her.&quot;</p><p>Allison, who had a sister, Lauren, loved her family and teachers especially.</p><h2>Rachel D'Avino, 29</h2><p>Police told her family Rachel D'Avino, a behavioural specialist, died after shielding one of the students, said Lissa Lovetere Stone, a friend of D'Avino's, from her home town of Bethlehem.</p><p>Days before she was killed, D'Avino's boyfriend had asked her parents for permission to marry her. Anthony Cerritelli planned to ask her on Christmas Eve, Lovetere Stone told the Associated Press.</p><p>D'Avino, who had only begin working at the school, was someone whose &quot;job didn't end when the school bell rang at 3 o' clock,&quot; said Lovetere Stone.</p><p>Lovetere Stone said she met her friend in 2005 when D'Avino was assigned to her son, who has autism. D'Avino was so dedicated she'd make home visits and constantly offered guidance on her son.</p><p>&quot;I'm heartbroken. I'm numb,&quot; Lovetere Stone said. &quot;I think she taught me more about how to be a good mother to a special needs child than anyone else ever had.&quot;</p><h2>Dawn Hochsprung, 47</h2><p>Hochsprung, the principal of Sandy Hook elementary school, mother of two daughters and three stepdaughters, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/dec/15/dawn-hochsprung-sandy-hook-elementary.\">led her school according to her own values of creativity</a>, inclusiveness and academic ambition. </p><p>Her pride in her school and wider community was obvious. She would send memos to parents addressed to the &quot;Sandy Hook family&quot;. She would tweet photos showing glimpses of life there. On the week before the shooting, she tweeted images of fourth-graders rehearsing for their winter concert; before that, the hands of kindergarteners exchanging play money at their makeshift grocery store. The New York Times said she had introduced &quot;Wacky Wednesdays&quot; when students came to school in mismatched clothes. She would often join in herself, dressing up and bringing her poodle to school.</p><p>Officials said she died while lunging at the gunman in an attempt to overtake him.</p><p>Gerald Stomski, first selectman of Woodbury, where Hochsprung lived and previously taught, told the AP: &quot;She had an extremely likeable style about her. She was an extremely charismatic principal while she was here.&quot;</p><h2>Nancy Lanza, 52</h2><p>Nancy Lanza was the divorced mother of Adam Lanza, 20, and the first of the 27 victims he killed. She was shot dead in her bed, with one of her own guns, in the home they shared. She leaves behind another son, Ryan, 24.</p><p>She was described by friends as social and generous to strangers, <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/16/nyregion/friends-of-gunmans-mother-his-first-victim-recall-her-as-generous.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss&amp;smid=tw-nytimes&amp;_r=0\">according to the New York Times</a>, but also highly strung, as if she were holding herself together. Relatives, friends and former classmates said she struggled to help Adam cope with a developmental disorder that often left him reserved and withdrawn.</p><h2>Anne Marie Murphy, 52</h2><p>Anne Marie Murphy, a special education teacher at Sandy Hook elementary school, had four children herself. She was a good mother, wife and daughter and was artistic, fun-loving, witty and hard working, her parents, Hugh and Alice McGowan, said.</p><p>She died trying to shield one of her students, Dylan Hockley, six, from the barrage of bullets that would kill them both. He died in the arms of the teacher he loved, said Dylan's mother, Nicole. Their bodies were found together, Dylan wrapped in her arms.</p><h2>Lauren Gabrielle Rousseau, 30</h2><p>Lauren Gabrielle Rousseau had wanted to be a teacher from the age of three. She spent years working as a substitute teacher and doing other jobs. So when she finally got the job as full-time teacher at Sandy Hook, last year, she was thrilled, her mother said.</p><p>Her mother, Teresa Rousseau, told the Danbury News-Times: &quot;It was the best year of her life.&quot;</p><p>&quot;Lauren wanted to be a teacher from before she even went to kindergarten,&quot; she said. &quot;We will miss her terribly and will take comfort knowing that she had achieved that dream.&quot;</p><p>She was described as gentle, spirited and active and loved music, dance and theatre.</p><h2>Mary Sherlach, 56.</h2><p>Mary Sherlach, the school psychologist, and mother of two daughters, had worked at Sandy Hook for 18 years, giving support and guidance to young children. It was going to be her last year, in a job she loved, John Button, a friend of her husband, told the New York Times. When the shots began, Sherlach and the school principal ran towards the shooter and lost their lives in the process.</p><p>Her son-in-law, Eric Schwartz, told the South Jersey Times that Sherlach rooted for the Miami Dolphins, enjoyed trips to the Finger Lakes, and relished helping children overcome their problems. She had planned to leave work early on Friday, he said, but never had the chance. In a news conference, Schwartz said the loss was devastating, but that Sherlach was doing what she loved.</p><p>&quot;Mary felt like she was doing God's work,&quot; he said, &quot;working with the children.&quot;</p><h2>Victoria Soto, 27</h2><p>Victoria Soto, the teacher who died trying to protect her first-graders, has been described as a dedicated educator who had her dream job.</p><p>Her cousin, Jim Wiltsie, a police officer, said the family had been told that Soto, who has been at Sandy Hook for five years, was attempting to get her class into a closet when the gunman entered the room. &quot;In our eyes, she's a hero,&quot; Wiltsie told ABC News.</p><p>&quot;She was trying to shield, getting her children into a closet and protect them from harm. And by doing that put herself between the gunman and the children and that is when she was tragically shot and killed.&quot;</p><p>Wiltsie said the family had taken some comfort in knowing that Soto died while doing a job that she loved.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/401418535|2012-12-22T11:49:02Z|bcb04dc0807496a1de07ca3c7c81ab159af6cb29 -->","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2012-12-20T22:05:52Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","score":"1.0","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/16/1355669881910/Teachers-and-pupils-of-Sa-001.jpg","standfirst":"Families and friends of the victims have spoken publicly about their loved ones in the week since the Sandy Hook shootings<br /><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/interactive/2012/dec/20/newtown-shooting-victims-tribute\">Newtown shootings: the victims remembered</a>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3ckgq","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/16/1355669881910/Teachers-and-pupils-of-Sa-001.jpg","wordcount":"3285","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"401418535","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Karen McVeigh","publication":"guardian.co.uk","internalPageCode":"1845557","shouldHideAdverts":"true","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-12-23T20:34:05Z"},"tags":[{"id":"world/newtown-shooting","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webTitle":"Newtown shooting","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/newtown-shooting","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/newtown-shooting","references":[]},{"id":"world/connecticut","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionNam